				<div class="info">
					<span class="printuser avatarhover"><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dreverettmann" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(323946); return false;"  ><img class="small" src="http://www.wikidot.com/avatar.php?userid=323946&amp;amp;size=small&amp;amp;timestamp=1610223783" alt="DrEverettMann" style="background-image:url(http://www.wikidot.com/userkarma.php?u=323946)"/></a><a href="http://www.wikidot.com/user:info/dreverettmann" onclick="WIKIDOT.page.listeners.userInfo(323946); return false;" >DrEverettMann</a></span> <span class="odate time_1274322682 format_%25e%20%25b%20%25Y%2C%20%25H%3A%25M%7Cagohover">20 May 2010 02:31</span>
														</div>
			</div>
			<div class="content" id="post-content-788890">
									

<p>Thanks on the Deadpool test. That just didn't quite fit.</p>
<p>I've answered your questions in chat, but for future reference, the main article explains that, yes, he does change to fit whatever species would most make sense in the context of the story. For example, becoming a dwarf in the Hobbit. In Watership Down, he'd become a rabbit.</p>
<p>For the second question, as the article explains, he's very good at avoiding injury while in a story, using narrative tropes to his advantage. He has an instinctive ability to figure out the safest place in a story and stay there. I've some ideas for what would happen if he [i]were[/i] injured, but I'm saving those for a story.</p>
<p>I've also edited the Gadsby test. Fred <em>generally</em> goes by that name, but he doesn't have to.</p>

							</div>

								
					
